    <h1>Calcium Channel Blocker (CCB) Toxicity</h1>
    
    <div class="alert">
        <strong>"One Pill Can Kill" Warning:</strong> A single adult therapeutic dose of a CCB (especially extended-release verapamil or diltiazem) can cause profound bradycardia, hypotension, and cardiovascular collapse in a toddler.
    </div>

    <h2>Clinical Presentation</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Vitals:</strong> Hypotension, bradycardia (though dihydropyridines like amlodipine may initially cause reflex tachycardia).</li>
        <li><strong>ECG:</strong> PR prolongation, AV blocks, various arrhythmias.</li>
        <li><strong>Metabolic:</strong> Hyperglycemia (CCBs block insulin release from the pancreas), metabolic acidosis.</li>
        <li><strong>Neuro:</strong> Altered mental status secondary to hypoperfusion.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr>

    <h2>Weight-Based Resuscitation & Antidotes</h2>

    <div class="calc-box">
        <h3>1. Calcium Therapy</h3>
        <p>Administer to overcome competitive blockade at the calcium channel. Improves inotropy more than chronotropy.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Calcium Gluconate 10%:</strong> 60 mg/kg (0.6 mL/kg) IV over 5-10 minutes. Max single dose: 3 g. <em>(Preferred for peripheral IV)</em></li>
            <li><strong>Calcium Chloride 10%:</strong> 20 mg/kg (0.2 mL/kg) IV over 5-10 minutes. Max single dose: 1 g. <em>(Requires central line to avoid tissue necrosis)</em></li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-box">
        <h3>2. Glucagon</h3>
        <p>Stimulates adenylate cyclase independent of the beta-receptor, increasing intracellular cAMP and calcium.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Pediatric Dose:</strong> 50 mcg/kg (0.05 mg/kg) IV bolus over 1-2 minutes.</li>
            <li><strong>Max Single Dose:</strong> 5 mg.</li>
            <li><strong>Note:</strong> May cause profound vomiting. Premedicate with antiemetics and ensure airway protection.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-box">
        <h3>3. High-Dose Insulin Euglycemia Therapy (HDI)</h3>
        <p>Improves myocardial carbohydrate utilization in the severely stressed, hypotensive heart. <strong>First-line for severe toxicity.</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Regular Insulin Bolus:</strong> 1 Unit/kg IV.</li>
            <li><strong>Regular Insulin Infusion:</strong> Start at 1 Unit/kg/hr IV. May titrate up to 10 Units/kg/hr based on hemodynamic response.</li>
            <li><strong>Dextrose Bolus:</strong> 0.5 g/kg IV (Use D25W or D10W for young children) <em>only if</em> blood glucose is < 200 mg/dL.</li>
            <li><strong>Dextrose Infusion:</strong> Start at 0.5 g/kg/hr IV. Titrate to maintain blood glucose between 100-250 mg/dL.</li>
            <li><strong>Potassium:</strong> Keep K+ between 2.8 - 3.2 mEq/L. Do not supplement unless K+ drops below 2.8 mEq/L, as total body potassium is not depleted.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-box">
        <h3>4. Vasopressors</h3>
        <p>Used concurrently with HDI for persistent hypotension.</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Norepinephrine:</strong> Start at 0.05 - 0.1 mcg/kg/min IV. Titrate to effect.</li>
            <li><strong>Epinephrine:</strong> Start at 0.05 - 0.1 mcg/kg/min IV. Titrate to effect.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-box">
        <h3>5. Lipid Emulsion Therapy (Intralipid 20%)</h3>
        <p>Consider for refractory cardiogenic shock, especially with highly lipophilic CCBs (e.g., verapamil).</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Bolus:</strong> 1.5 mL/kg IV over 1 minute. (May repeat up to 2 times for persistent cardiovascular collapse).</li>
            <li><strong>Infusion:</strong> 0.25 mL/kg/min IV.</li>
            <li><strong>Max Total Dose:</strong> 10-12 mL/kg.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

